ring that the top-level is public and matches the exact test directory package.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test configurations**\\n\\nI might face CI test failures if port 8082 is used. To avoid this, it’s probably a good idea to check if the port is available first and select an alternative if it’s not. I can't configure the port directly. Using `@ResourceLock(\\\"tcp-8082\\\")` doesn’t solve the external issue. JUnit assumptions could skip tests, but coverage needs to be considered. It might be possible to write a test that addresses error handling for when the Agent can't start due to the port being in use.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test method structure**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the test method that would try to start a new Agent and check if it's registered. If there’s a RuntimeException, I could assert that the message contains \\\"8082,\\\" which seems reasonable. However, I need to consider if this approach might skip any important metadata checks or cause a new instance to fail. I want to ensure that everything necessary is covered without missing anything crucial. Finally, I'll make sure to include cleanup to avoid any leftover states.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_4zkxBmAaaLmIt0TmGejxUzmo|fc_0b30cb71746fd624016a23d6f5219881938b1a5e195728aa4a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-1.2-api/2.18.0 -maxdepth 3 -type f -print | sort | xargs -r -n1 echo"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2418, "output": 2832, "cacheRead": 20992, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 26242, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780733622774, "responseId": "resp_0b30cb71746fd624016a23d6b73f188193a5657ab3e40efb9e"}}
