e concise, but maybe some modifications are expected. I’m wondering if I should use `org.apache.logging.log4j:log4j-1.2-api:2.18.0`, but that doesn’t contain the shaded HtmlAdapter. Also, using Java's `javax.management.loading.MLet` for remote loading might not work.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering instructions about dependencies**\\n\\nI’m thinking through the user’s request regarding adding test dependencies if needed, or explaining why the call site isn't reached. It’s clear I shouldn’t include any code and probably need to note that I didn't compile or run tests as per the instructions. I’ll finalize with a summary that explains the status and the reasoning behind it. Looks like I don’t need any tools for this. Got it!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "No test changes were made.\n\n`org.apache.log4j.jmx.Agent.startServer()` is only reachable through the public `Agent.start()` path after `Agent.createServer()` successfully loads:\n\n```java\nClass.forName(\"com.sun.jdmk.comm.HtmlAdapterServer\")\n```\n\nThat class belongs to the old optional JDMK/JMX RI dependency referenced by Log4j, but it is not available as a usable Maven Central JAR:\n\n- `com.sun.jdmk:jmxtools:1.2.1` exists only as metadata/POM, with no downloadable JAR.\n- Maven Central class search did not find `com/sun/jdmk/comm/HtmlAdapterServer.class` or the related `HtmlAdaptorServer` class in any indexed artifact.\n\nUnder the repository rules, I cannot satisfy this by adding a fake `com.sun.jdmk.comm.HtmlAdapterServer` test class, generating a replacement class, or reflectively invoking the private `startServer()` method directly. Those would either shadow a dependency API or bypass the supported public API.\n\nSo the two remaining call sites in `org.apache.log4j.jmx.Agent` should remain uncovered unless a real, compatible JDMK artifact providing `com.sun.jdmk.comm.HtmlAdapterServer` is added to the test classpath.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0b30cb71746fd624016a